1. INTRODUCTION 

1.1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

Parallel Energy LP (Parallel Energy) owns and operates the Zofness Natural Gas Booster Station (Zofness Station) located in Dumas, Texas.  Natural gas and associated liquids enter the Zofness Station through pipelines with various diameters ranging from 8 inch to 22 inch.  The Zofness Station includes facilities for the following; gas, water and condensate separation; gas compression, and vapor recovery.  The inlet gas and liquid handling system separates inlet fluids into gas, free water and condensate and routes each fluid as follows:



     Gas flows to the Gas Compression System;

     Water flows to the Separated Water Storage and Injection System;

     Condensate flows either to the Condensate Stabilization System or, temporarily, to Product Storage Tanks.



There are seven (7) condensate storage tanks in operation at Zofness station.  The largest condensate storage tank is limited by administrative controls to 300 barrels.  For the purpose of this assessment, the largest tank is assumed to be filled to 300 barrels (12,600 gallons), which is equivalent to 70,459 lbs condensate.  



Under the authority of section 112(r) of the Clean Air Act, the Chemical Accident Prevention Provisions require facilities that produce, handle, process, distribute, or store certain chemicals to develop a Risk Management Program, prepare a Risk Management Plan (RMP), and submit the RMP to EPA. Covered facilities were initially required to comply with the rule in 1999, and the rule has been amended on several occasions since then, most recently in 2004.  The regulated chemicals at Zofness Station consist of specific flammable hydrocarbons present within the natural gas liquid (NGL, or "condensate) and gas streams within the plants.  The regulated hydrocarbons include:



     Methane;

     Ethane;

     Propane;

     Butane; and

     Pentane.



